  "id": "hebben-zijn",
  "language": "dutch",
  "title": "Hebben or Zijn",
  "subtitle": "In the perfect tense, which helper verb does it take?",
  "question": "Which helper verb in the perfect tense?",
  "tip": "Picture the verb. If something moves to a place or changes into a new state, reach for zijn. For everything you simply do, reach for hebben. A fast wrong tap still teaches you the tricky one.",
  "left": {
    "label": "HEBBEN",
    "bullets": [
      "Most verbs use hebben: eten, drinken, kopen, lezen, doen.",
      "Activities you perform: werken, spelen, koken, slapen, lachen.",
      "Verbs that act on an object: zien, geven, helpen, betalen.",
      "When in doubt, pick hebben, you are right more than half the time."
    ]
  },
  "right": {
    "label": "ZIJN",
    "bullets": [
      "Movement toward a place: gaan, komen, vertrekken, aankomen.",
      "Change of state: worden, vallen, sterven, groeien, stijgen.",
      "Fixed exceptions: blijven (stay) and zijn itself (geweest).",
      "Disappearing or moving house: verdwijnen, verhuizen, ontstaan."
    ]
  },
